<font color="#FF0000">ON BEING ME, AND BEING COOK B.</font><br>
<tt>Mon Jul 28 20:39:22 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook: Look at the top of your screen, see the word &quot;dialogue&quot;? That means this is a place of dialogue, of exhanging thoughts and ideas, of sharing feelings, of listening and talking.  It does not meet posting the most long winded posts in the world. Nor does it mean ignoring questions posed to you. It means exchanging ideas, not forcing your own opinion on others. Can you stop being such a one sided chest beating gorilla?<br><br>
You say C.O.'s are a red flag to you because of some bag of rice or the like. If the broad brush you used to paint C.O.'s was any larger, it would be a rollar used to paint 12 lane highways.  Allow me to educate you about what &quot;I did during the war, daddy,&quot; and that I am DAMN PROUD of it all.<br><br>
Having witnessed first hand a real war, (see previous posts) I returned to the United States, resumed my very active anti-war protesting and draft counseling, and probably saved overf 100 confused and lost souls who would have been sucked up into the military because they didn't know they had any other options. I never encouraged anyone to go to Canada.  When Local Draft Board 125 in Long Beach said I was I-A and sent me down to the Induction Center for a physical, I went. I handed out informatio that was not &quot;communist propaganda&quot;a but sincere draft options and choices. Education is not brain washing, by the way.  The brass didn't like what I was doing, trying to wake up the docile sheep, so I got beated up and kicked out.  Real tough Military guys, slapping around a hippie in his shorts.  Brave men.  This happened twice before my local draft board decided to punt me to the FBI and the Government. Then the states were that I get a C.O. status or do 5 years hard labor.<br><br>
I am not a religious man. Not now, not then. Not a Quaker, just a JEW (Boy, now you know I am a commie, right? I'm sure you think I have horns too, drink babies blood, and run the international zionist communist banking system, right?).  I stood my ground with the Selective Service System, that THIS WAR WAS WRONG. Not all wars, JUST THIS ONE.  And I won. I prevailed.  I was the very first American to ever be granted a Conscientious Objector status on NON-RELIGIOUS grounds.  The system ruled, after a protracted (that means long) legal battle that &quot;my beliefs in the wrongness of the Viet Nam War were equal to those religious beliefs of those opposed to war in general&quot;.<br><br>
What did I fight 4 years to win Cook? I fought to stay in my country and stand up to my country and say it was wrong. I fought for the right to have to defend myself weekly against every redneck who hated anyone with hair over his ears. But more importantly, I fought and won and proved my point then, that that war in Viet Nam was wrong, and now 30 years later history has proven me right.<br><br>
I don't need to quote unnamed people in unnamed letters to prove my point.  Look around you, your loyalty to your government is to be admired, 30 years ago. Your constant name calling and waving your ignorance around now like the bloody flag is pitiful, now, and not the sign of a hero or anyone worth emulating.  Rather, you come across as a tragic figure stuck in the past. (Leave that to Gallager, he's funnier).  <br><br>
Meanwhile, from 1969 to 1971 I worked the night shift for over one year doing bedpans on a ob/gyn (babies) floor at Harbor General Hospital in Torrance, Cook, you know, near South Central L.A. (i.e. the ghetto). Then I spent a year working with the disabled, both years for the County of Los Angeles.  Sure I got a salary and I got to go home when not at work.  (I never said what I did was equal to being in the bush).  When I completed my two years of &quot;civilian service&quot; I felt that I had contributed to my country.  I returned to college and applied for G.I.Bill benefits.  Why not, I had made my contribution too, althought not as gory and traumatic as yours.  No benefits for civilian service I found out.  You know what, Cook, it didn't matter. I just got a second job and continued on to Grad School by day, and free clinic counselor/draft counselor at night.<br><br>
I did not agree with the amnesty for those who went to Canada (most stayed by the way), and I never called anyone a &quot;baby killer&quot; or a &quot;murderer&quot;.  I have laid on train tracks and been beated by policemen. I have had redneck Marines want to &quot;give me&quot; a haircut, and I have been heckled over and over because I choose back then to have long hair.  Standard line: &quot;Hey Boy, you sure stink. Are you a boy or a girl under that hair, Huh?  Why don't I beat the shit out of you and find out&quot;.  I heard that a hundred times if I heard it once.<br><br>
So Cook, you asked me what I did during the war, I hope I gave you an answer that you can understand, and PERHAPS you can begin to understand what a dialogue is.<br><br>
One goodl question deserves another, so I will leave you with one:  <br><br>
If you are the mighty killing soldier that you claim to be, why did you only serve one tour?  Why didn't you re-enlist and continue to fight for your beliefs?  <br><br>
Most of the Veterans I have grown to know and care for on this site did more than one tour. Why not you?<br><br>
Doc Spatz
